In article ha4@nyx10.cs.du.edu, colin@nyx10.cs.du.edu (Colin Plumb) writes:
>In article <2qlpjc$chr@ame2.math.arizona.edu>,
>Steve Uurtamo <uurtamo@math.arizona.edu> wrote:
>> Make SURE (absolutely sure) that p+1 and p-1 and q+1 and q-1 do not 
>> divide into lots of little factors.  Same thing with pq-1 and pq+1.
>
>Um... why?  Every mathematician I have spoken to assures me this is
>not important.  It was important before the elliptic curve methods
>of factorisation came along, but since then it's just a fable that
>people keep repeating.
>-- 
>	-Colin


Maybe not for just factoring, but for RSA, (p-1) and (q-1) should not have too
many small factors. This is necessary to ensure that messages will be encrypted
with high order.
(cf. Simmons and Norris attack in Cryptologia '77)

